@node Installation-and-Getting-Started "2. Installation and Getting Started"

                    @{fg highlight}2. Installation and Getting Started
                    ===================================@{fg text}


   Diavolo Backup can be automatically installed on your hard drive.
Simply click on the file "Install_Diavolo" (found on the accompanied disk)
with your mouse and follow all instructions.

   After a successful installation, you will find Diavolo in the Directory
that You have chosen.  Normally, a "Diavolo" will be found on your hard
drive.  Simply start the program by double-clicking on the icon "Diavolo".

   The install procedure allows you to create a bootable Diavolo Backup
disk. With this disk you can start Diavolo Backup, even if your hard drive
has become invalid and your system won't startup.

   To start Diavolo Backup, open the drawer the install program has
created on your drive and double click on the Diavolo Backup icon.

   After a few seconds Diavolo's main menu will be displayed. You have now
the choice to

   @{" Backup  " Link Saving-with-Diavolo}
   @{" Restore " Link Restoring-Software}
   @{" Compare " Link Comparing-Backups}


   Or you can use the right mouse button to browse through the
@{" Pull-Down menus " Link Pull-Down-Menu}.


   Continue guide tour with

       @{"  3. Saving with Diavolo                " link Saving-with-Diavolo}

@endnode
@node Saving-with-Diavolo "3. Saving with Diavolo"

                           @{fg highlight}3. Saving with Diavolo
                           ======================@{fg text}


   The first and most important step in a backup program without a doubt
is the saving of data.  The ways to do this are shown in this capital,
although it does not go into every detail possible.

   Next, click on the function "Backup".  Diavolo Backup now brings up
another window; the so-called "Device Selection".  In this window, you
should choose @{b}WHAT@{ub} and @{b}WHERE@{ub} you wish to save your data.

   With the three switches in the upper left-hand corner, You can decide
if the backup should go on diskettes ("Disks"); an Amiga-DOS File ("File",
also for cangeable media or on a SCSI-Streamer device, respectively.

   @{b}A BACKUP TO THE RAM-DISK IS IMPOSSIBLE, CONSIDERING THE FACT THAT IT
WOULDN'T MAKE MUCH SENSE ANYWAY!@{ub}

   For each of the three above mentioned switches (directly right of each)
is the possibility for further editing.


   When saving to diskettes, you must decide which drives will be used and
if the data written should be checked ("Verify" ie.  Read-after-Write).
Using this option will find defective disks and will allow you to replace
them.

   Normally, "Verify" should generally always be turned on.  Otherwise, a
backup could easily prove to be useless.  The amount of time won as a rule
isn't worth the risk.

   If you don't want to save your data to disks, see the specific capitals
for other backup media:

   @{" Backup to file / removable media " Link Saving-on-Removable-Media}
   @{" Backup to SCSI Streamer devices  " Link Saving-on-Streamer}


   The list in the middle of the window shows you all data devices that
are currently available.  The text in parenthesis shows, for each entry,
the actual device name.  Under "Selected" a zero is shown (for each
device) at first, because you have not yet chosen any data.

   Continue guide tour with

       @{"  3.1 Selecting files to backup         " Link Select-Data}
       @{"  3.2 Backup in Progress                " Link Backup-in-progress}

@endnode
@node Select-Data "3.1 Selecting files to backup"

                       @{fg highlight}3.1 Selecting files to backup
                       -----------------------------@{fg text}


   Double-click on the Data-device that you wish to make a backup of.

   Diavolo Backup now opens a new window, in which it is possible to
follow how this data-device is searched.  When all the data has been read,
the "Diavolo Select Window" is shown.


   All directories and sub-directories on your hard drive are shown on the
left side of the window using the so-called "Tree" Depiction.
Sub-directories are therefore set slightly to the right of their parent
directories.  You can see the sub-directories belong to their
parent-directories by the lines that connect them together.

   All data is shown on the right side, is found under the currently
selected / active directory from the left side of the window.

   With a simple click of the mouse you should pick a directory with the
somewhat unusual method of depiction used.  It takes a bit of getting
used to, but you will soon find out that there is no better way to get the
best overview than this method!

  To choose a directory for backup, simply double-click on the entry of
choice.  This directory, and all directories under it, are now selected,
and will appear as if they are "raised".  Also, the data that is shown in
the right window will also have that "raised" look and are selected for
backup.

   To activate the entire partition, just double-click on it's name in the
very first line found in the left window.

   Choosing with the double-click (an alternative is the single-click
while holding the shift-key) works like a on-off switch:  When the
directory has not been selected, double-clicking on it will select it.  If
it is selected, and you double-click on it, then the directory will be
de-selected.

   Also, each of the files in the right window can be selected /
un-selected in the same manner as the directories.  After choosing a file,
on the second click, continue holding the mouse pressed.  Doing this
allows you to choose multiple files by moving the mouse over them without
having to double-click on each one.


   The selection window has many more options, but for the basic
functions, Diavolo Backup has to offer is not so important.  The options
will be discussed in depth in a @{" later capital " Link Data-Choice}.  When you are satisfied
with your choice of files to be saved, click on "Return" to return to the
previous window; that is, back to the "Device Selection" window.


   In the "Selected" area, you now see that the partition that you have
chosen is raised, and the amount in bytes are shown from the directories
and files you have selected.

   You can now continue to choose more partitions to backup, or make
changes on any partitions that you have already selected.

   Should a device fail to appear in the list, or if you intend to save a
logical assignment, then enter it's name into the "Other Volume" field.
If the logical device is recognized, it will join the others in the
"Mounted Volumes" list.  You may then choose the data to be saved in the
manner previously discussed.  Multi-assignments are also supported in the
same way.

   It occurs often that one may want to backup only a certain directory
from a hard drive.  It can be very annoying to have to scan an entire
partition just for one directory.  Some partitions are very large, and can
take a long time to scan.  Because of this, there is a function called
"Select directory".  By pressing this, a system requester will appear,
allowing you to choose any directory you wish.  After you have chosen a
directory, it will be included with the other entries in the "Mounted
Volumes" list, and then scanned.

Below you see the summary of the data you have chosen.

   @{b}THE STATEMENTS CONCERNING TIME AND THE AMOUNT OF DISKETTES ALWAYS
DISPLAYS THE OUTCOME UNDER THE MOST UNFAVOURABLE CONDITIONS.  DEPENDING ON
THE PACKER USED AND THE TYPE OF DATA BEING COMPRESSED, THE TIME AND SIZE
OF THE BACKUP WILL BE LOWER AND MAY EVENTUALLY NEED ONLY HALF AS MANY
DISKS AS ORIGINALLY SPECIFIED.@{ub}

   When you are ready to proceed with you backup, then click on
"Start Backup".

   Before the backup starts, you will be asked to enter a title for the
backup.  This name will assist you in identifying the backup at a future
date.

   In the same dialogue you may activate Diavolo's password protection.  if
"Use password" is checked, you can enter up to 10 characters in the password
field.  The Password keeps unwanted individuals from access to your private
data.  If you also check the "Encrypt backup" option, all the data will be
encrypted using the password and the selected XPK encryption algorithm (see
chapter @{" 8.2 Backup Options  " link Backup-Options} for details).

   NOTE:

     If you are saving to disk, it is not possible to deactivate the data
     encryption when using a password. The "rebuild backup" option for
     disk backups would restore a protected backup even without the
     password if the data is not encrypted.

   NOTE:

     If you enable the data encryption the backup speed will slow down
     drastically, especially while saving to high-speed streamers.

   @{b}IF YOU DO DECIDE TO ENTER A PASSWORD, THEN MAKE SURE YOU REMEMBER
IT.  IT IS IMPOSSIBLE TO RESTORE AN ENCRYPTED FILE IF YOU DO NOT KNOW THE
PASSWORD!  THERE IS NOT EVEN A WAY WE COULD HELP YOU!  DON'T FORGET THE
PASSWORD.

   THE PASSWORD CAN BE UP TO 10 LETTERS LONG.  CAPITAL AND LOWER-CASE
LETTERS ARE RECOGNIZED AS BEING DIFFERENT!@{ub}


   Continue guide tour with

       @{"  3.2 Backup in Progress                " Link Backup-in-progress}

@endnode

@node Backup-in-progress "3.2 Backup in Progress"

                           @{fg highlight}3.2 Backup in Progress
                           ----------------------@{fg text}


   When you've entered the backup's password and title, the backup really
gets underway.  Diavolo Backup will now show you the "Diavolo Backup in
Progress" window.

   In this window, you see the process of the backup optically depicted:
At the top, all information concerning Directories and files.  In the
middle, the packer and the efficiency, and at the bottom, the status of
the backup medium, in this case, the drives and diskettes.

   When you're saving to files or to streamer tapes, the display and the
procedure will differ slightly, see the chapters

   @{" Backup to file / removable media " Link Proceed-on-Removable-Media}
   @{" Backup to SCSI Streamer devices  " Link Proceed-on-Streamer}


   The saving process itself is very simple:  Follow all instructions that
the Computer tells you (Don't worry, the computer won't command you to do
anything that might hurt you...)

   Now, you must insert the first diskette in a drive.  If you have
already inserted the diskette before now, then confirm this by clicking on
"repeat" in the requester.

   You can insert the diskettes in any order you wish; that is, if you
need more than one.  If you own High Density drives, then you can use them
also with High Density Diskettes.  These types of drives have double the
capacity of the normal drives.  When a disk is full and finished, Diavolo
Backup shows this in the lower left-hand quarter of the picture with:
"Replace Disk".  Remove the diskette and correctly mark it.  You should
immediately insert an empty diskette in the drive as soon as you have
removed one.

   @{b}IMPORTANT NOTE:

   IF YOU HAVE MORE THAN ONE HIGH DENSITY DRIVE, YOU MUST WAIT UNTIL
DIAVOLO POPS UP THE REQUESTER FOR THE NEXT DISK BEFORE YOU REMOVE THE LAST
DISK AND INSERT THE NEXT ONE.  THERE IS A FLAW IN THE AMIGA'S OPERATING
SYSTEM, THAT MAKES IT IMPOSSIBLE TO RECOGNIZE MORE THAN ONE HD DISK
SIMULTANOUSLY.@{ub}

   On the left is shown how many disks will be needed.  This amount is
constantly being updated, directly affected by the packer's packing
efficiency and the data being compressed.  Diavolo Backup always
calculates Double Density diskettes as measurement units.  If you are
using High Density diskettes, then simply divide the number of Double
Density diskettes shown by two.  You should assume that one HD diskette is
equal to two DD diskettes.

   The right side shows how many diskettes have been written and are
finished.  Here, each disk will be counted exactly as one, regardless if
it is a HD or DD diskette.

   If you didn't "feed" your diskette drives fast enough, or if you own
only one drive, then Diavolo Backup will show a requester telling you that
another diskette is required.  Simply insert a diskette in the drive.  The
request will disappear after a moment or two, just the way your Amiga
normally reacts.

   The "Pause/Abort" button, at the bottom right side of the window,
brings a requester up, asking you if you want to stop the backup.  As long
as this requesters shown, the backup is paused.  An unfinished backup can
NOT be restored!

   Other requesters that Diavolo Backup shows will not stop the backup
process.  You might receive the message that a new diskette is needed, and
still see the program reading and packing in the background.  This is a
one of the major advantages of Diavolo Backup.

   If a disk proves to be defective, Diavolo will warn you with the
appropriate requester -- as long as you haven't disabled the "Verify"
function.  You have the choice of either replacing the entire diskette, or
skipping over the defective track.  You should only skip a track if you do
not have enough disks to complete the backup -- mainly because these type
of defective disks can be very unstable and therefore un-reliable.

   After the last diskette of the backup has been written, Diavolo Backup
will request the first diskette again.  Insert this disk, or click
"Repeat" if the diskette already is in the drive.

   Diavolo Backup writes a file directory to the first disk.  This is data
that the backup will need when restoring data.  When this process is
finished, Diavolo Backup shows you some statistical information about the
backup.

   You now have the choice of immediately return to the main menu, a
complete data list of the saved files, or to check the saved data once
again.

   The data list will be explained in detail later.

   If your backup is really important, then you should under no
circumstances, refrain from checking the data a second time.  Diavolo
Backup will read the entire backup an compare it with the original
contents of the hard drive(s).


