@node Restoring-Software "4. Restoring Software"

                           @{fg highlight}4. Restoring Software
                           =====================@{fg text}


   The time will come, of course, when you will want to restore your data.

   Choose the function "Restore" from the main menu.  You will then find
yourself in the "Device Selection" window.  Restoring data is almost
identical to saving with the exception of a few changes.  One difference
is that the device list is not present.

   Before any of the options become active, the contents of a backup must
be read.

   To read the contents of a backup, you must choose on which media that
the backup exists (diskettes, file, or SCSI-device).  The adjustment
options are exactly the same as previously explained when @{" saving data " Link Saving-with-Diavolo}.

   After you have correctly adjusted the media options, then click on "Read
backup directory".  Diavolo Backup now opens another window which allows you
to see the process of the backup being read. If you did not have the first
diskette inserted, then Diavolo requests that you do so.

   If you have problems with your backup (e.g.  defective or missing first
disk), you can select "Rebuild".  Diavolo then scans all disks of the
backup to rebuild the file catalog.  You can skip missing or defective
disks, but - of course - all files stored on a skipped disk cannot be
Restored.  If the last disk of the backup set is not available, select
Cancel to finish the scanning process.

   If your backup was made with the encryption option, a requester will
now ask you to enter the password.  Successful restoration of the backup
will only occur after you have entered the correct password.

  You can now follow how the beginning of the first disk is searched.
After a few seconds you will see "Backup directory complete".  You will
also see the name of the backup (that is, if you gave it a name) and the
date it was made.  Click in the requester on "OK".

   If you have chosen the wrong backup, then simply press again on "Read
backup directory" and insert the first diskette of the backup in question.

   All saved partitions appear in the list.  If you wish to restore the
entire backup to the same device (or devices) it came from, then click on
"Start restore".  However, you can edit the data lists similar to the way
explained before in choosing the files to be saved (see chapter
@{" File Selection " Link Data-Choice} for details).

   You also can choose for each device it's own destination to be
restored.  Click on the data in which the destination is to be changed,
then click on the field "Destination".  You can also use the "Select"
button to choose the destination with the help of the system file
requester.  Remember that the device shown in the destination field is
where each entry in the file list will go to.

  When you are satisfied that all options are correct, then begin the
restoration by clicking on "Start restore".

   The restore process is similar to the save process with the exception
of two additional information fields.

   Under "Files not written" the amount of files that were not restored
are shown, because they already exist on the destination device.  You can
alter how Diavolo Backup reacts when this occurs, which will be explained
in chapter @{" 8.3 Restore options " Link Restore-Options}.

   The field "Unreadable files" shows how many files that were not
restored due to missing or damaged disks.

   Should a problem occur while a disk is being read (because of a damaged
disk), then you have two choices.  You can skip the defective track, in
which the file(s) are certainly lost, or you can exclude the entire disk.
The latter causes all data on that disk not to be restored.

   Should a disk become lost or misplaced, all is not lost.  Your backup
can still be partially restored by skipping over the missing disk(s).

   You can control how Diavolo Backup reacts when it encounters data that
already exists while it is restoring.  The information is covered detail
in chapter in chapter @{" 8.3 Restore options " Link Restore-Options}.  If you have not yet edited this
option, then Diavolo Backup will always ask before taking action.  You
have the choice of:  replacing, skipping, or altering the option for the
endurance of the restoration process.

   After the restoration process has ended, you will again be shown some
statistical information.  (Programmers can be very conceited!) If some
data was no longer readable, or not written, then it is advisable, that
you output a data list by pressing "Error Report".  This way, you can find
exactly which files that were affected. The "File Report" gives you a 
list of all files in the backup with some in-depth information about each
file.

   Continue guide tour with

       @{"  5. Comparing Backups                  " Link Comparing-Backups}

   or select another chapter from the @{" Table of Contents " Link main}.

@endnode
@node Comparing-Backups "5. Comparing Backups"

                            @{fg highlight}5. Comparing Backups
                            ====================@{fg text}


   When comparing the data of a backup, no data is written or altered.
Instead, the contents of the backup is compared with the data on the hard
drive.  This way, you have an excellent possibility to test your backups
for accuracy.

   The compare process is almost completely identical to the restore
process.  During this process, there are a few different information fields
to be seen.

   @{fg fill}"Identical files"@{fg text} are all data that has passed the compare test.  That
is, the files in the backup are identical to those found on the hard drive.
Correspondingly, @{fg fill}"Mismatching files"@{fg text} are those which have shed light on
differences found while being compared.

   Under @{fg fill}"Missing files"@{fg text}, the number specified are files that were in the
backup, but did not exist on the hard drive.

   If the backup is older, it is possible that certain files have been updated
since that time, and will be shown as @{fg fill}"Newer files"@{fg text}.

   @{fg fill}"Unreadable files"@{fg text} are data which (also like restoring) could no longer be
read because of diskette errors.

   Every file has information about it's contents.  (Such as:  comments, or
protection bits).  When this information is inconsistent, then the file will
fall under the category @{fg fill}"Fileheader mismatch"@{fg text}.

   Also like the restore process, the compare process has it's statistics.
If all data was not identical, it is advised to get an error file list to see
exactly which files were affected.



   Now you have completed the most important chapters.  The guide tour ends
with this chapter.  There are many additional features covered in the
remaining chapters

