@node Subsequent-Saving-Options "6.2 Subsequent Saving Options"

                       @{fg highlight}6.2 Subsequent Saving Options
                       -----------------------------@{fg text}


   Generally, each hard drive should occasionally be backed up.  But under
normal circumstances, not all data is altered.  Data that has been changed
is usually only a small percentage of the hard drive.

   It makes sense to make a backup of the entire hard disk, and then only a
backup of the data that has been changed since then.

   Exactly for this reason, Amiga-DOS offers the so-called "Archive bit".
The Archive bit (or flag) exists for each file on you hard drive.  Every
backup program, Diavolo Backup included, should set this bit for each file
that has been saved (as long as this option has not been explicitly turned
off).  As soon as a file is changed, Amiga-DOS un-sets this bit again.  In
this way, you can always see which files have been added or changed since
the last backup.

   So, you make an entire backup of you data.  And, after a certain amount
of time (frequency depending on how important your data is), you can make a
subsequential backup.

   This can be done as followed (assuming you are now in the Selection window):

   · Click on the Advanced selection options

   · Choose @{fg fill}"Unset"@{fg text} from the @{" Archive bits " Link Archive-Bits} cycle menu.

   · Activate the @{" Inclusive " link Selection-modes} button, as you wish to include all new data.

   · Now select the directories that you wish to make a subsequent backup
     of.  If you wish to do this with the entire hard drive, then simply
     double-click the name of the drive in the very first line.  Using this
     method, Diavolo Backup will activate all data where the archive bit is
     no longer set.

   · Return to the device selection window by pressing @{fg fill}"Return"@{fg text} and start the
     backup.

   You can repeat this process as often as you wish.  Keep in mind, that you
will need a new set of disks for every subsequent backup.

   To completely restore your data, start with the first complete backup,
and then restore each subsequent backup in the order that you made them.


   There are more examples of data selections in the chapters

               @{" 6.3 Selecting data before a certain date " link Selecting-data-before-a-certain-date}
               @{" 6.4 Excluding certain data groups        " link Excluding-certain-data-groups}

   or select any other chapter from the @{" Table of Contents " Link main}.

@endnode
@node Selecting-data-before-a-certain-date " 6.3 Selecting data before a certain date"

                  @{fg highlight}6.3 Selecting data before a certain date
                  ----------------------------------------@{fg text}


   With the option @{" Dated after " link Dated-After-options} you can, as previously explained, select
all data that was made after a certain date.

   How to do exactly the opposite (select data that is older than a certain
date), is described in the next paragraphs.

   · Click on the Advanced selection options

   · Activate the @{" Inclusive " link Selection-modes} option.  Double-click on all directories you
     wish to backup. All data including the younger files will be selected.

   · Now activate the @{" Exclusive " Selection-modes} option in order to reduce the amount of files
     from the chosen ones.

   · Select the @{" Dated after " link Dated-After-options} option and enter the date in question to the
     field directly on the right.

   · Double-click on the volume entry at the top of the directory tree (left
     window).  You will now see that all the data, that was made or modified
     after the date entered, is now de-selected.  Only the older data is
     left over (still selected.)

   Appropriately, you should use the same method when changing one of the
other options to get the opposite effect.


   There are more examples of data selections in the chapters

               @{" 6.2 Subsequent Saving Options            " link Subsequent-Saving-Options}
               @{" 6.4 Excluding certain data groups        " link Excluding-certain-data-groups}

   or select any other chapter from the @{" Table of Contents " Link main}.

@endnode
@node Excluding-certain-data-groups "6.4 Excluding certain data groups"

                     @{fg highlight}6.4 Excluding certain data groups
                     ---------------------------------@{fg text}

   Often, one will want to exclude certain datatypes from a backup.  For
example, those files that end with the .lha and .info suffix.  Although
Amiga-DOS offers pattern matching, it is hard to handle.  Because of this,
there is a simple way of getting around this problem in Diavolo Backup:

   · Click on the Advanced selection options

   · Activate the @{" Inclusive " link Selection-modes} option.  Double-click on all directories you
     wish to backup.  All data including the unwanted files will be
     selected.

   · Now activate the @{" Exclusive " link Selection-modes} option in order to reduce the amount of
     files from the chosen ones.

   · Activate the @{" Pattern Option " link Filter-and-Pattern-Options}, and enter "#?.info" in the field to
     the right (without the quotation marks).  Double-click on the volume
     entry at the top of the directory tree (left window).  All data that
     ends with the suffix ".info" will now be de-selected.

   · Change the @{" Pattern option " link Filter-and-Pattern-Options} to "#?.lha". double-click again on the
     volume entry.  Now, all data that ends with the suffix
     ".lha" is de-selected. All the other data remains unchanged.

   You can combine all of these possibilities together, to achieve a more
specialized selection of criteria.


   There are more examples of data selections in the chapters

               @{" 6.2 Subsequent Saving Options            " link Subsequent-Saving-Options}
               @{" 6.3 Selecting data before a certain date " link Selecting-data-before-a-certain-date}

   or select any other chapter from the @{" Table of Contents " Link main}.

