@node Buffer-Size "Buffer size"

                                @{fg highlight}Buffer size@{fg text}


   The @{fg highlight}"Buffer size"@{fg text} controls the size of the internal memory to be used.
Diavolo Backup needs this memory for the exchange of data between three
different tasks.  The larger the buffer, the more data Diavolo Backup can
process in advance.  maybe you have noticed that Diavolo Backup is already
busy reading and packing data, although you have not yet inserted a disk to
be written.  The program uses this memory to store the processed data until
it can be finally written.

   Similarly, the same applies to Restore and Compare.

   The optimal buffer size depends on your system and on what medium you are
saving to.

   For backups to disk, a buffer size of 800 KB is sufficient.

   For backups to files or SCSI streamer tapes it may be usefull to increase
the buffer size beyond 1 MB, especially if your hard drive contains many
smaller files. As most hard drives slow down when reading many small files,
the buffer helps to maintain a constant data stream.

   Systems with lower amounts of memory (1.5 MB or less) should not be
adjusted to more that 120 KB.

   If Diavolo Backup is the only active application, you could also set the
slider to "max available" (right-most setting).  Then Diavolo will allocate
as much memory that is available for its internal buffer (there will be a
small amount of memory left free - about 200 k - to allow the system to
operate within safe conditions).


