  "Ask name & password"

    Diavolo Backup will ask you for a name and password, at the beginning of
    a backup, only if this button has been selected.  If you do not need
    this option, then simply de-select it. This will spare you from having to cancel
    a requester with each backup.


  "Use ExAll()"

    ExAll() is a new option under the AmigaOS 2.04, that allows a quicker
    search of directories.

    Every now and then with certain configurations problems have come up.

    If you have problems when scanning directories, then disable this
    option.  Diavolo will then use the normal AmigaOS 1.3 method of
    scanning.


   Continue with

           @{" Hardlink Options " link Hardlink-Options}

           @{" 8.1 Global Options  " link Global-Options}
           @{" 8.2 Backup Options  " link Backup-Options}
           @{" 8.3 Restore Options " link Restore-Options}

   Or select any other chapter from the @{" Table of Contents " Link main}.

@endnode
@node Hardlink-Options "Hardlink Options"

                              @{fg highlight}Hardlink Options@{fg text}


   If you are not familliar with the concept of links, then ignore these
features and leave both options set.


  "Save HL'ed dirs"

    That means "Save hardlinked directories".

    If you set this options, hardlinks to directories will be saved
    symbolically.  If not, the link will be saved as normal directories.

    When the link is saved symbolically, Diavolo only notices to which
    directory the link is connected to.  When restoring, Diavolo then will
    setup all links the way they were when the backup was made - @{b}AFTER
    ALL@{ub} the data has been written.  Your harddrive will end up exactly
    the same as it was when the backup was made.

    In the second case, the link will be saved just as any other directory,
    and Diavolo will read all the files contained in this directory as if it
    were a normal directory.  When restored, it would be re-produced as a
    standard directory.

    Softlinked directories are always saved symbolically.

    @{b}**WARNING**@{ub}

      It is possible to create an endless loop from directories by, for
      instance, making a hardlink directory to the current directory.
      Diavolo would then scan the directory without end.


    @{b}NOTE:@{ub}

      If you change one of the hardlink options, you must make sure to
      remove all filelists (by selecting in the menu "Project" the
      menu-option @{b}"Clear all filelists"@{ub} and finally re-scanning the
      partitions.


  "Save HL'ed files"

    Meaning "Save hardlinked files"

    If you set this options, hardlinks to files will be saved symbolically.
    If not, the link will be saved as normal files.

    When the link is saved symbolically, Diavolo only notices to which data
    the link is connected to.  When restoring, Diavolo then will setup all
    links the way they were when the backup was made - @{b}AFTER ALL@{ub}
    the data has been written.  Your harddrive will end up exactly the same
    as it was when the backup was made.

    In the second case, the link will be saved just as any other file, and
    would be re-produced when restored.  After a complete backup and then a
    restore, the link would be replaced with the real data.

    @{b}NOTE:@{ub}

      If you change one of the hardlink options, you must make sure to
      remove all filelists (by selecting in the menu "Project" the
      menu-option "Clear all filelists" and finally re-scanning the
      partitions.


    Softlinked files are always saved symbolically.


   Continue with

           @{" 8.1 Global Options  " link Global-Options}
           @{" 8.2 Backup Options  " link Backup-Options}
           @{" 8.3 Restore Options " link Restore-Options}

   Or select any other chapter from the @{" Table of Contents " Link main}.

@endnode
@node Restore-Options "8.3 Restore Options"

                            @{fg highlight}8.3 Restore Options
                            -------------------@{fg text}


   The Restore option window will appear

   · when you choose the item @{fg highlight}"Restore options"@{fg text} from the menu @{fg highlight}"Options"@{fg text} or

   · while restoring a backup where a file already exists, and the option
     "Ask before replacing existing file" is selected.

   When Diavolo Backup is restoring data to the destination device, and
encounters a file with the same name as in the backup, it needs to know how
it should react.

   You have six different possibilities to choose from, in which only one
can at a time, can be active:


           @{" Ask before replacing existing file " link Ask-before-replacing-existing-file}
           @{" Keep existing files untouched      " link Keep-existing-files-untouched}
           @{" Replace existing files             " link Replace-existing-files}
           @{" Replace older files                " link Replace-older-files}
           @{" Rename existing files              " link Rename-existing-files}
           @{" Restore with different name        " link Restore-with-different-name}


   @{fg highlight}Rebuild directory structure@{fg text}

     Normally, Diavolo Backup restores the data exactly the way it found it.

     By deactivating this option Diavolo Backup will simply write the
     contents of the backup into the directory have chosen, without worrying
     about the original directory structure.

     This option is only useful when restoring only certain files to a
     certain directory.

     This option cannot be altered during the restore process.


   Other option windows:

           @{" 8.1 Global Options " link Global-Options}
           @{" 8.2 Backup Options " link Backup-Options}

   Or select any other chapter from the @{" Table of Contents " Link main}.

@endnode
@node Ask-before-replacing-existing-file "Ask before replacing existing file"

                  @{fg highlight}Ask before replacing existing file@{fg text}


   If this option is selected, Diavolo Backup will warn you it has found
that the data already exists.  You can overwrite the data, skip the file
(the data will not be overwritten), or change the options.

   It is better the you choose the latter option if there are many files to
be restored.

   Continue with

           @{" Keep existing files untouched " link Keep-existing-files-untouched}
           @{" Replace existing files        " link Replace-existing-files}
           @{" Replace older files           " link Replace-older-files}
           @{" Rename existing files         " link Rename-existing-files}
           @{" Restore with different name   " link Restore-with-different-name}

           @{" 8.1 Global Options  " link Global-Options}
           @{" 8.2 Backup Options  " link Backup-Options}
           @{" 8.3 Restore Options " link Restore-Options}

   Or select any other chapter from the @{" Table of Contents " Link main}.

@endnode
@node Keep-existing-files-untouched "Keep existing files untouched"

                        @{fg highlight}Keep existing files untouched@{fg text}


   When you choose this option, Diavolo Backup will not overwrite any of the
existing files.  Files with the same name will not be restored.  During and
after the restore process, you can see the number of files that were not
written.  If you choose the file report option after the restoration, you
can see those files that were not restored.


   Continue with

           @{" Replace existing files      " link Replace-existing-files}
           @{" Replace older files         " link Replace-older-files}
           @{" Rename existing files       " link Rename-existing-files}
           @{" Restore with different name " link Restore-with-different-name}

           @{" 8.1 Global Options  " link Global-Options}
           @{" 8.2 Backup Options  " link Backup-Options}
           @{" 8.3 Restore Options " link Restore-Options}

   Or select any other chapter from the @{" Table of Contents " Link main}.

@endnode
@node Replace-existing-files "Replace existing files"

                           @{fg highlight}Replace existing files@{fg text}


   If you want to restore all the data regardless of the files that already
exist, then choose this option.


   Continue with

           @{" Replace older files         " link Replace-older-files}
           @{" Rename existing files       " link Rename-existing-files}
           @{" Restore with different name " link Restore-with-different-name}

           @{" 8.1 Global Options  " link Global-Options}
           @{" 8.2 Backup Options  " link Backup-Options}
           @{" 8.3 Restore Options " link Restore-Options}

   Or select any other chapter from the @{" Table of Contents " Link main}.

@endnode
@node Replace-older-files "Replace older files"

                          @{fg highlight}Replace older files@{fg text}


   This option makes sure that only files which are older than the files
found on the backup will be replaced.


   Continue with

           @{" Rename existing files       " link Rename-existing-files}
           @{" Restore with different name " link Restore-with-different-name}

           @{" 8.1 Global Options  " link Global-Options}
           @{" 8.2 Backup Options  " link Backup-Options}
           @{" 8.3 Restore Options " link Restore-Options}

   Or select any other chapter from the @{" Table of Contents " Link main}.

@endnode
@node Rename-existing-files "Rename existing files"

                         @{fg highlight}Rename existing files@{fg text}


   All files that already exist will be renamed if you choose this option.

   The new name will have the original name with the suffix ".orig" added.
If this name already exists, then a number such as ".orig2" will also be
added.


   Continue with

           @{" Restore with different name " link Restore-with-different-name}

           @{" 8.1 Global Options  " link Global-Options}
           @{" 8.2 Backup Options  " link Backup-Options}
           @{" 8.3 Restore Options " link Restore-Options}

   Or select any other chapter from the @{" Table of Contents " Link main}.

@endnode
@node Restore-with-different-name "Restore with different name"

                      @{fg highlight}Restore with different name@{fg text}


   The last possibility is to restore the data with a different name.

   The name of the files that are restored will have it's original name with
the suffix ".rest" added.  Note also that a number will be attached to files
that already exist having the ".rest" suffix.


   Continue with

           @{" 8.1 Global Options  " link Global-Options}
           @{" 8.2 Backup Options  " link Backup-Options}
           @{" 8.3 Restore Options " link Restore-Options}

   Or select any other chapter from the @{" Table of Contents " Link main}.

@endnode
@node Saving-on-Removable-Media "9. Saving to File or on Removable Media"

                  @{fg highlight}9. Saving to File or on Removable Media
                  =======================================@{fg text}


   One of the special abilities of Diavolo Backup, is the possibility of
using any type of removable media that is recognized by Amiga DOS.

   Some examples would be media as SyQuest removable hardrives or one of the
many different magnet-optical systems.


   From the main menu, click on the function "Backup".  Diavolo Backup now
brings up another window; the so-called "Device Selection".  In this window,
you should choose @{b}WHAT@{ub} and @{b}WHERE@{ub} you wish to save your data.

   Activate the "File" button as the target.  The name should reflect the
removable drive.  (For instance: "SyQuest:Backupfile"). With the "Select"
Button you can bring up the standard system file requester to select the
destination file more easily.

   The list in the middle of the window shows you all data devices that
are currently available.  The text in parenthesis shows, for each entry,
the actual device name.  Under "Selected" a zero is shown (for each
device) at first, because you have not yet chosen any data.  See the
chapter

   @{" 3.1 Selecting files to backup " Link Select-Data}

   or continue with

   @{" 9. Saving to File or on Removable Media (continue) " Link Proceed-on-Removable-Media}

@endnode

@node Proceed-on-Removable-Media "9. Saving to File or on Removable Media (continue)"

   After you have started the backup process, Diavolo Backup immediately 
begins to write to the given file.

   If the media should become full or the given filename is invalid, Diavolo
Backup will open a requester.  Change the media at this time, and press
"Repeat".  If needed, a different path can be chosen by pressing "Change
path" where a different file name (and path) can be entered.

   Diavolo displays the name of the currently written file, the size of the
file written and the free space of the backup medium.

   The "Pause/Abort" button, at the bottom right side of the window,
brings a requester up, asking you if you want to stop the backup.  As long
as this requesters shown, the backup is paused.  An unfinished backup can
NOT be restored!

   Other requesters that Diavolo Backup shows will not stop the backup
process.  You might receive the message that a new diskette is needed, and
still see the program reading and packing in the background.  This is a
one of the major advantages of Diavolo Backup.

   When the backup has been finished, Diavolo Backup will request the first
medium (or file) of the current backup, to write the backup directory.

   When this process is finished, Diavolo Backup shows you some statistical
information about the backup.

   You now have the choice of immediately return to the main menu, a
complete data list of the saved files, or to check the saved data once
again.

   If your backup is really important, then you should under no
circumstances, refrain from checking the data a second time.  Diavolo
Backup will read the entire backup an compare it with the original
contents of the hard drive(s).


   Continue with

       @{" 10. Saving to SCSI Streamer Devices    " link Saving-on-Streamer}

   or select any other chapter from the @{" Table of Contents " Link main}.

@endnode

@node Saving-on-Streamer "10. Saving to SCSI Streamer Devices"

                     @{fg highlight}10. Saving to SCSI Streamer Devices
                     ===================================@{fg text}


   A backup program is not really useful unless one has a type of media
capable of storing large amounts of data.  Lately, the Tape Streamers have
become inexpensive and more efficient which, in turn produces higher
expectations on the software being used.

   The Streamer support from Diavolo Backup has been totally re-designed to
keep up with the newest developments in Streamer technology.

   A major strength of Diavolo Backup against other programs is it's
adaptive ability.  Not to mention Diavolo Backup's speed.

   First, all the neccessary adjustments will be explained step-by-step,
without slowing you down with too many details.

   You have to setup Diavolo Backup for your SCSI and streamer
configuration:

    @{" 10.1 Streamer configuration            " link SStreamer-configuration}


   The neccessary steps for creating, verifying and restoring backups on
streamer tapes are explained in the chapters

    @{" 10.2 Backup to Streamer tape           " link SBackup-to-Streamer-tape}
    @{" 10.3 Restoring or comparing with tapes " link SRestoring-or-comparing-with-tapes}
    @{" 10.4 Backup to multiple tapes          " link SBackup-to-multiple-tapes}


   Additional tools for the work with streamer tapes are provided within the
'SCSI Support' pull-down menu.

    @{" 10.5 The Menu 'SCSI Support'           " link SThe-Menu-SCSI-Support}


   You now know all that is important to Backup, Restore, or Compare with
streamer tapes and Diavolo Backup.  The next sections have more in-depth
information that might make your life a bit easier in tight situations with
Diavolo.

    @{" 10.6 The Index files                   " link SThe-Index-Files}
    @{" 10.7 SCSI Adjustments                  " link SSCSI-Adjustments}
    @{" 10.8 SCSI Reselection                  " link SSCSI-Reselection}
    @{" 10.9 Optimizing Diavolo for Streamers  " link SOptimizing}


   Select any other chapter from the @{" Table of Contents " Link main}.

@endnode
@node SStreamer-configuration "10.1 Streamer Configuration"

                         @{fg highlight}10.1 Streamer configuration
                         ---------------------------@{fg text}


   The first step is - as always - the configuration.  As long as the
streamer is not replaced, then you will only need to do this configuration
once.

   After you have started Diavolo Backup, choose from the menu under "SCSI
Support" the option "SCSI Adjustments".

   A window will open containing all the options needed for streamer
support.

   Most of these options are adjusted by Diavolo Backup automatically.
Only the following steps you must do yourself.

   - In the field "Device name" you must enter the name of the SCSI device
     driver.  If you are not sure of this, then check in your SCSI
     controller's handbook or call the manufacturer.  Below is a list of
     the most commonly used controllers and their devices:

     o  All Commodore Controllers (A3000, 2091 etc.):    scsi.device
     o  GVP Controllers:                                 gvpscsi.device
     o  bsc ALF 2/3:                                     ALF.device
     o  bsc Oktagon:                                     oktagon.device
     o  Masoboshi:                                       MASOBOSHI.device

     Take note that the device drivers are case sensitive!

     NOTE:

       Make sure that the software of your controller is the newest version
       possible.  Many problems with the streamer can be remedied by
       updating the ROMs of the controller.  Turn to the manufacturer of
       the controller for more information.


   - In the field "Unit" you should enter the SCSI unit number that you
     have set the streamer to.  As a rule, this number will be from 0 to 6.
     If you are not sure then simply try one after another.


     After you have entered the device name and unit correctly, information
     about the streamer will be shown in the field to the right.  When you
     see "Device Type:  Streamer tape", you have found the streamer.


   - the button "Inquiry" will again ask for the data of the chosen device.
     If the information shown on the right side of the window does not
     correctly reflect the streamer, then press this button.


   - Diavolo Backup will need to know more about the special abilities of
     the streamer.  The program will figure these out itself.  The only
     thing needed is a tape for the streamer.  Be warned that this test
     WILL destroy any information found on the tape!  Insert the tape into
     the streamer and then press the button "Check capabilities" After you
     have answered the warning requester, Diavolo Backup will do a number
     of different tests with your streamer.  The duration time  of this test
     depends on the model of the streamer.

   - When Diavolo is finished, it will have achieved the best adjustments
     for optimum performance of the streamer.  Normally you will not have
     to do any further adjustments.

   - If you wish to learn more about the different options, then take a
     look at the chapter @{" 10.7 SCSI Adjustments " Link SSCSI-Adjustments}.


   Okay, that's it.  Press "OK" and then save the new adjustments (right
Amiga-key + S).  Diavolo is now almost ready for the first backup.

   Here is a list of the adjustments of the other menu-options that will
help to achieve optimum performance with a streamer.  More details to these
options are found in chapter @{" 8. Adjustments " Link Adjustments}.

   - Packer (@{" Backup options " Link Backup-Options})

     Because most streamers are very fast, it doesn't make much sense to
     use a compression algorithm.  The streamer would only be slowed down.
     Set the packer option to "No Compression".


   - Buffer Size (@{" Global options " Link Global-Options})

     This buffer is used to hold the data that has been read from the hard
     drive, but has not yet been written to the tape.  The larger the
     buffer, the better the backup.  things will run smoother and faster
     with a large buffer.  It is best if you set this adjustment to the
     maximum.


   - Task priority (@{" Global options " Link Global-Options})

     With slower devices (such as Diskettes or very slow streamers), it is
     better to set the "Priority of disk/streamer task" to 1.  It is
     better to set this adjustment to 0 for faster streamers.  All other
     settings should be set to 0.


   For more details on reaching optimum performance, see section
@{" 10.9 Optimizing for streamer " Link SOptimizing}.  Read there if you are not satisfied with
the speed of Diavolo.


   The neccessary steps for creating, verifying and restoring backups on
streamer tapes are explained in the chapters

    @{" 10.2 Backup to Streamer tape           " link SBackup-to-Streamer-tape}
    @{" 10.3 Restoring or comparing with tapes " link SRestoring-or-comparing-with-tapes}
    @{" 10.4 Backup to multiple tapes          " link SBackup-to-multiple-tapes}


   Select any other chapter from the @{" Table of Contents " Link main}.

@endnode
@node SBackup-to-Streamer-tape "10.2 Backup to Streamer tape"

                        @{fg highlight}10.2 Backup to Streamer tape
                        ----------------------------@{fg text}


   From the main menu, click on the function "Backup".  Diavolo Backup now
brings up another window; the so-called "Device Selection".  In this window,
you should choose @{b}WHAT@{ub} and @{b}WHERE@{ub} you wish to save your data.

   Activate the "Device" button as the target.  The name of your streamer
should be shown right of this button. You can alter the settings for your streamer
with the "SCSI Settings" button, for example if your streamer's name is not
shown. See chapter @{" 10.1 Streamer configuration " Link SStreamer-configuration} for details.

   If you wish to compare the data immediately after backup, then activate the
option "Verify". This option is found to the right of the device settings
button. you can still compare the data even if you do not activate this option
before a backup. You must only press a button after the backup process has
ended.

   The list in the middle of the window shows you all data devices that are
currently available.  The text in parenthesis shows, for each entry, the
actual device name.  Under "Selected" a zero is shown (for each device) at
first, because you have not yet chosen any data.  See the chapter

   @{" 3.1 Selecting files to backup " Link Select-Data}

   or continue with

   @{" 10.2 Backup to Streamer tape (continue) " Link Proceed-on-Streamer}

@endnode
@node Proceed-on-Streamer "10.2 Backup to Streamer tape (continue)"

   After a short time, you will be asked to insert a tape (this step is of
course skipped if a tape is already inserted).

   Diavolo will try to identify the tape.  If you have previously used this
tape for backups, Diavolo will recognize the tape and will bring up a list
of all backups found on it.

   If the tape has not yet been used, or formatted by another program,
Diavolo will notice this, and give you the option of writing to this tape,
or choosing another.

   NOTE:

     It is possible that Diavolo could recognize a tape, but not be able to
     find the index file belonging to the tape.  It is still possible to
     read and restore, but it is no longer possible to save to this tape.
     (This may change in future versions of Diavolo).  See section
     @{" 10.6 The Index files " Link SThe-Index-Files}.


   The following paragraphs assumes that Diavolo has correctly identified
the tape and a list of all backups is shown.

   Most streamers will only allow data to be added to a tape or totally
re-written.  Only some newer streamers (specifically DAT streamers) can
write to tape starting with any backup that may exist.

   Diavolo backup already knows if this you streamer has this option (see
section @{" 10.1 Streamer configuration " Link SStreamer-configuration}).

   Depending on the abilities of the streamer you can choose either:  from
which backup Diavolo should start, if Diavolo should completely write over
ALL existing data or if the new backup should be appended to the existing
data.

@{b}**WARNING**

   All backups that are raised in blue will be destroyed.  Be EXTREMELY
careful when choosing!@{ub}

   When you have chosen where the backup should start at, then press "OK" or
the Return-key.  If you would rather backup to a different tape, then press
"Change tape".

   By pressing "OK" Diavolo starts the backup.

   When the backup has finished, an information window will open.  You have
the choice of "Compare", which compares the data on tape to the data on hard
drive.  If you have checked the "Verify" checkmark in the "Device selection"
window before, Diavolo will automatically start the verification process.


   If your backups are larger than the capacity of your tapes then you can
create multiple tape backups:

    @{" 10.4 Backup to multiple tapes          " link SBackup-to-multiple-tapes}


   The neccessary steps for verifying and restoring backups on streamer
tapes are explained in chapter

    @{" 10.3 Restoring or comparing with tapes " link SRestoring-or-comparing-with-tapes}


   Additional tools for the work with streamer tapes are provided within the
'SCSI Support' pull-down menu.

    @{" 10.5 The Menu 'SCSI Support'           " link SThe-Menu-SCSI-Support}


   Select any other chapter from the @{" Table of Contents " Link main}.

@endnode
@node SRestoring-or-comparing-with-tapes "10.3 Restoring or comparing with tapes"

                   @{fg highlight}10.3 Restoring or comparing with tapes
                   --------------------------------------@{fg text}


   Here you should also do as explained in chapter
@{" 4.  Restoring Software " Link Restoring-Software}.

   After you have pressed "Read backup directory" Diavolo will try to
identify the tape.

   If Diavolo recognizes the tape, then you will see a list showing all
existing backups.  Simply choose the backup to be restored from the list.

   If you have erased data from the hard drive, then it is possible that
Diavolo is unable to find the directory of the tape.  You will receive
"Error while reading tape index.  DOS Error:  object not found".  Choose
"Search tape".  Diavolo will then manually search the tape for backups.
When one is found you receive a notice about this backup.  You can either
use the backup, or continue searching.

   NOTE:

     Diavolo can always restore the data, regardless if the index file
     exists on the hard drive or not.  The backup will take noticably longer
     if the index file is not found.  The streamer must go to the end of the
     backup to retrieve needed information.  This operation can take as long
     as the backup itself with some streamers, so have patience!

   Diavolo then positions the tape to read the directory information of the
backup.  This can take some time with certain streamers.  This happens in a
matter of seconds with DAT streamers or when the backup is the first one on
the tape.

   When the Directory has been read, you can now choose the information to
be restored or compared, as explained in chapter 4.  If the entire contents
of the backup should be used, the simply press "Start Restore" or "Start
Compare" (Whichever applies).


   If your backups are larger than the capacity of your tapes then you can
create multiple tape backups:

    @{" 10.4 Backup to multiple tapes          " link SBackup-to-multiple-tapes}


   Additional tools for the work with streamer tapes are provided within the
'SCSI Support' pull-down menu.

    @{" 10.5 The Menu 'SCSI Support'           " link SThe-Menu-SCSI-Support}


   Select any other chapter from the @{" Table of Contents " Link main}.

@endnode
@node SBackup-to-multiple-tapes "10.4 Backup to multiple tapes"

                       @{fg highlight}10.4  Backup to multiple tapes
                       ------------------------------@{fg text}

   Diavolo supports multiple tape backups.

   When a tape is full, it is automatically re-wound and - if possible -
ejected.  You will then be asked to insert a new tape.  You will be able -
as explained above - to select from which position the backup should
continue.

   Make sure that this tape still has room for more data.

   This process will repeat until the backup is accomplished.

   When restoring or comparing, you must insert the first tape that was used
for the backup and then follow the instructions as explained in section
@{" 10.3 Restoring or comparing with tapes " Link SRestoring-or-comparing-with-tapes}.  If required, Diavolo will
request for you to insert a certain tape.

   If no index file exists for the multiple tape backup, then you
should still do as stated above.  When Diavolo asks you then insert the
*LAST* tape of the backup, then do so.  Diavolo will then be able to read the Directory
information of the backup.

   NOTE:

     Because of technical problems with many streamers, after making a
     backup that extends over multiple tapes, you should *ALWAYS* compare
     the data.  If problems should arise, then consult the text file
     "Problems & Solutions".


   Additional tools for the work with streamer tapes are provided within the
'SCSI Support' pull-down menu.

    @{" 10.5 The Menu 'SCSI Support'           " link SThe-Menu-SCSI-Support}


   Select any other chapter from the @{" Table of Contents " Link main}.

@endnode
@node SThe-Menu-SCSI-Support "10.5 The Menu 'SCSI Support'"

                        @{fg highlight}10.5 The Menu "SCSI Support"
                        ----------------------------@{fg text}


  @{fg highlight}"SCSI Settings"@{fg text} (Amiga-I)
    This menu option opens the adjustments window for the SCSI options.
    More details about this are found in section @{" 10.7 SCSI Adjustments " Link SSCSI-Adjustments} of
    this text.

  @{fg highlight}"Rewind tape"@{fg text} (Amiga-<)
    Does just that. The tape will be rewound to the beginning.

  @{fg highlight}"Retense tape"@{fg text} (Amiga->)
    Through much tape rewinding, it is possible that the tape could become
    loosely wound.  This could cause problems.  This option will completely
    retense the tape.

    This is normally not needed with modern streamers.

  @{fg highlight}"Eject tape"@{fg text} (Amiga-dash)
    If your streamer supports software controlled tape ejection, it is
    possible to select this menu option to eject the tape.  The tape will
    always be rewound first.

  @{fg highlight}"Erase tape"@{fg text}
    The entire tape will be erased.  You have the choice of physically
    erasing the whole tape ("Complete"), or if the data on the tape should
    be made unreachable ("Fast").

    Some streamers can not distinguish a difference between these different
    methods.

    NOTE:

      If your tape is divided into multiple partitions, then Diavolo will
      give you the choice of erasing each partition, or to format the tape
      making one large partition.  We advise you to do the latter if you
      wish to use the tape with Diavolo.


   More in-depth information is covered in the following chapters:

    @{" 10.6 The Index files                   " link SThe-Index-Files}
    @{" 10.7 SCSI Adjustments                  " link SSCSI-Adjustments}
    @{" 10.8 SCSI Reselection                  " link SSCSI-Reselection}
    @{" 10.9 Optimizing Diavolo for Streamers  " link SOptimizing}


