@endnode
@node SThe-Index-files "10.6 The Index files"

                            @{fg highlight}10.6 The Index files
                            --------------------@{fg text}


   Diavolo makes a directory for each backup tape on your hard drive.  These
directories hold lists of all files in each backup and a file that contains
a list of all backups.  (Are you confused yet?) (Smile).

   These lists are used by Diavolo to get all the neccesary data needed in a
very fast way.  As most streamers are a bit slow by nature, this speed
things up when it comes to addressing tapes.

   Diavolo can of course, restore every backup even if the index directories
are missing.  (See section @{" 10.3 Restoring or comparing with tapes " Link SRestoring-or-comparing-with-tapes}.)

   Even so, it is not a bad idea to copy the index directories to disk to
speed up a restore process.  You could use Diavolo to make a backup of those
directories.


   The index directories and their files are found under the directory name
that has been entered in the menu option "SCSI Settings".  This directory
was originally named "Tape Catalogs" and was placed in the same directory as
the Diavolo program.


   More in-depth information is covered in the following chapters:

    @{" 10.7 SCSI Adjustments                  " link SSCSI-Adjustments}
    @{" 10.8 SCSI Reselection                  " link SSCSI-Reselection}
    @{" 10.9 Optimizing Diavolo for Streamers  " link SOptimizing}


   Select any other chapter from the @{" Table of Contents " Link main}.

@endnode
@node SSCSI-Adjustments "10.7 SCSI Adjustments"

                            @{fg highlight}10.7 SCSI Adjustments
                            ---------------------@{fg text}


   All options in the SCSI settings menu are covered in detail in this
section.

  "Device name"

    You should enter here the name of the SCSI device for your controller.
    See section @{" 10.1 Streamer configuration " Link SStreamer-configuration}.


  "Unit"

    This field is where you adjust the unit number of the streamer. See
    section @{" 10.1 Streamer configuration " Link SStreamer-configuration}.


  "Inquiry"

    This options shows all information about the selected device.  This
    information is shown on the right-hand side of the window.  If no
    logical unit is found, then only a series of dashes will be shown.  If
    the return key is pressed when the "Unit" field is activated, then and
    inquiry will be done automatically.


  "Check capabilities"

    This allows Diavolo to automatically test the streamer to find out what
    it can or cannot do.  This button should be pressed at least once,
    before any changes are done to the other options, so that Diavolo can
    deactivate those options which the streamer is not capable of.


  "Tape catalog options"

    Right now you can only edit one field here.  Namely, the path where
    Diavolo will find the directory that contains the index directories.
    the default name for this directory is "Tape Catalogs"

    In the future, Diavolo should be able to support two partitions on a
    tape, where one partition will hold the directory information, and the
    other the actual backups.

    Standard: "Tape Catalogs"


  "SCSI data transfer options"

    All options found here are directly linked with data transfer to the
    streamer.

      "Memory"

        This is type of memory that will be used for the transfer buffer to
        streamer.  "Chip" means that only Chip-memory will be used.  "DMA"
        has to do with memory that is connected to Zorro-II DMA cards (24
        bit memory).  "Any" means the all available memory can be used.

        The difference between "DMA" and "Any" is only of importance for
        systems that have a 32 bit processor (68020 or better) and 32 bit
        RAM.  This type of RAM cannot be addressed by Zorro-II cards.  So if
        you have a Zorro-II DMA controller (i.e.  GVP controller), you
        should set this to "DMA".  Take note that this setting will use chip
        memory if you do not have 24 bit RAM.

        The following configurations can use the "Any" setting:
          - Amiga 3000
          - Controllers that are integrated on turbo cards
          - Controllers that cannot handle DMA
          - Zorro-III controllers (e.g. A4091, Fastlane Z3)

        For all other cards or when in doubt, use the "DMA".

        Should you encounter problems by backup or restoration, then select
        "Chip".

        Standard: "DMA"


      "Buffer (kB)"

        The size of the transfer buffer is set here.  This setting almost
        NEVER affects the speed.  Usually the backup will not go as smoothly
        with an oversized buffer.  Because of this, keep this field set to
        32 kB.

        For those streamers that have little or no internal memory, it may
        be neccesary to increase the buffer size.  It may even help to use
        many Megabytes.  If you streamer continuously winds back and forth
        while writing, you can try to increase the buffer.  See section
        @{" 10.9 Optimizing Diavolo for streamers " Link SOptimizing}.

        **WARNING**

          You should not enter more buffers than your controller can move at
          one time.  Consult the handbook of your controller when in doubt.
          This number is usually called "Max transfer".

        Standard: 32


      "Buffered"

        Just about every streamer on the market has it's own internal data
        buffer which makes the backup go as smooth as possible.

        If you have tested the abilities of your streamer, then Diavolo has
        recognized if it has these data buffers or not.

        When no internal buffer exists, then this field is ghosted (without
        a checkmark).  Some streamers do not allow this buffer to be
        disabled.  If this is the case, then field will still be ghosted
        (but with a checkmark).

        There is no good reason to disable the internal buffer unless there
        is a hardware defect in the streamer.

        Standard: Active (depending on the streamer)


      "Fixed blck."

        Here we meant the "Fixed Block length".  Streamers allow variable or
        fixed block sizes when writing.

        Also, this option is tested by Diavolo.  The field will be either
        available or ghosted depending on the streamers capabilities.

        As a rule, usage of fixed block length doesn't make as many problems
        as with variable block length.  Diavolo supports the latter mainly,
        so that those types of streamers can be used, even if they do not
        support fixed block length.

        Certain advanced functions in Diavolo only support fixed block
        lengths.

        Standard: Active (depending on the streamer)


      "(Max) Block size"

        You can enter the size of the blocks (or the maximum size when
        using variable blocks).

        The normal size is 512 bytes.  There is no good reason to change
        this.

        The maximum size depends on the streamer and the size of its data
        buffer.

        NOTE:

          Diavolo is normally able to restore almost any backup, regardless
          of the settings.  But, in this case the block size must always be
          correct, otherwise, Diavolo will not be able to identify the tape.
          Make a note of each block size for each tape if you change this
          before each restoration.

        Standard: 512 Bytes


  "Miscellaneous options"

    All of these option will speed up, or simplify working with your
    streamer.  Which of those you may use are decided by Diavolo
    automatically with the function "Check capabilities".

    **WARNING**

      You should NEVER activate any of these options without first running
      the "Check capabilities" test.  Diavolo deactivates all functions that
      do not function with your streamer.  With the option "Inquiry", all
      options are activated (That still doesn't mean that they can be used).


      "Setmarks"

        Setmarks is a feature that is only used by devices that support
        SCSI-II (See the field called "Supported SCSI version").

        When this option is active, Diavolo writes a setmark instead of a
        filemark to seperate different Backups.  Diavolo still writes
        filemarks within the backup to keep data properly separated.

        Some streamers can find Setmarks faster than Filemarks.

        Should Diavolo have problems when searching for backups, then
        deactivate this function and re-write the entire tape.  This option
        must be left either on or off for each tape.  It cannot be changed
        between each backup.


      "Fast locate"

        Almost every streamer allows many blocks to be skipped at one time.
        With some streamers it is faster to skip blocks than to read each
        one.  For most part, this function has not effect.

        Diavolo uses this option, only when certain parts of a backup are to
        be read to get to a certain place quicker.

        For SCSI technicians:  Diavolo uses the SPACE command with this
        function to skip the positive number of blocks.


      "Direct seek"

        This version is only active with SCSI-II.  With this function
        activated, Diavolo takes note of the block number of where a backup
        begins.  Some streamer have the ability to reel the tape to a
        certain block number very quickly.

        Also, this function is used by some streamers when skipping over
        blocks which can lead to better performance.

        This option is only supported with fixed blocks.

        For the SCSI-Technicians:  Diavolo uses the commands "READ POSITION"
        and "LOCATE" for this function.


      "Update in place"

        Almost all streamers that write multiple tracks can erase the entire
        tape or add to already written data, but cannot write over a certain
        position.

        This has much to do with the hardware concept of the streamer.

        Because of the spread of the ever-growing DAT streamers, which
        support writing over existing data while leaving previous data
        intact, this function can be very useful.

        The requirements are fixed block size and "Direct seek".

        With this function activated, you can choose any backup to be
        overwritten.


      "HW compression"

        Modern streamers support an internal compression; that is, the data
        is automatically packed while the backup is taking place.  This
        enlarges the tape's capacity, and speeds up the backup.

        If this option is active, then it makes no sense to active Diavolo's
        compression, which would slow the backup down.

        This option only sets a corresponding flag in the streamer itself.


      "Speed ctrl."

        Some streamers can adjust their speed to match the flow of data when
        reading or writing which keeps the streamer from winding forward and
        backwards to restart it's operation.

        This option only sets a corresponding flag in the streamer itself.


   More in-depth information is covered in the following chapters:

