@endnode
@node SSCSI-Reselection "10.8 SCSI Reselection"

                            @{fg highlight}10.8 SCSI Reselection
                            ---------------------@{fg text}


   There is a SCSI standard called "Reselection".  It is also referred to as
"Deselect/Reconnect" or something of that nature.

   This feature allows multiple SCSI devices to operate simultaneously
together.  For instance, a tape could be rewound and data could be read from
the hard drive at the same time.

   Some controllers have massive problems implementing reselection
correctly.  This is often only because the SCSI bus has been incorrectly
terminated.

  Diavolo is directly affected by this option, because it reads and writes
in a multi-tasking environment.

   If your computer locks up while making a backup (a steadily burning
hard disk LED is a typical symptom), then your controller of your steamer is
not designed for reselection.

   If this is the case, then consult the manufacturer of your controller, to
find a solution to this problem.  Some controller will allow reselction to
be disabled, but this causes massive speed loss.


   More in-depth information is covered in the following chapter:

    @{" 10.9 Optimizing Diavolo for Streamers  " link SOptimizing}


   Select any other chapter from the @{" Table of Contents " Link main}.

@endnode
@node SOptimizing "10.9 Optimizing Diavolo for Streamers"

                    @{fg highlight}10.9 Optimizing Diavolo for Streamers
                    -------------------------------------@{fg text}


   As a rule Diavolo works just fine when it has enough memory for the data
transfer buffer (found in Global options).  Multiple Megabytes couldn't
hurt.  The best is to give Diavolo all the free memory available.

   Normally it is better to deactivate Diavolo's internal packer to gain
some speed. But if the speed of backups to your streamer is less than
5 MB / Minute (shown while saving right above the percentage gauge) a fast
@{" compressor " Link Backup-Options} might improve the speed.  Best choice would be FAST.50 for
streamer (this is the default setting for fast compression).

   Diavolo's default setting for the @{" task priorities " Link Global-Options} is 0/0/1 (0 for
harddisk and packer task, 1 for disk/streamer task).  This is the optimal
setting for backups to disk drives.  For most streamer, it's much better to
set this to 0/0/0 (all three priorities to 0).

   If you have a 68030 or better, some 32 bit RAM and a controller which has
access to 32 bit memory (A3000, Zorro III controllers as Fastlane Z3 or
A4091 and controllers integrated on the accelerator board) then setting the
@{" transfer memory type " Link SSCSI-Adjustments} option to "ANY" will gain some speed.


   In some rare cases, the streamer will react to the smallest break in the
flow of data, and will stop and rewind, which directly affects the speed of
the process.

  In this case:

    - increase the @{" SCSI transfer buffer " Link SSCSI-Adjustments} to 1 or 2 MB (depending on your
      memory).  The Diavolo buffer size (in @{" Global options " Link Global-Options}) should be at
      least as large as the amount of memory in the SCSI transfer buffer.

    - set the @{" Priority of disk/streamer task " Link Global-Options} to 1.

    - Try using a fast @{" packing algorithm " Link Backup-Options} (such as FAST.50).  But then
      the Diavolo transfer buffer should be at least TWICE as large as the
      SCSI transfer buffer.


   Select any other chapter from the @{" Table of Contents " Link main}.

@endnode
@node Important-Notes "11. Additional Important Notes"

                       @{fg highlight}11. Additional Important Notes
                       ==============================@{fg text}


   @{b}Encrypting Backups@{ub}

     When encrypting of backups, Diavolo normally uses "FEAL.8" if you
     haven't altered the original settings.  This setting have proven itself
     and should be more than enough in any case.

     If you want even more data security, then raise the efficiency of FEAL
     (refer to @{" 8.2 Backup Options " Link Backup-Options}).


   @{b}DiskExpander, XFH@{ub}

     If you have compressed your harddrive with DiskExpander or XFH, you
     should not use Diavolo with compression.

     You cannot use the XPK libraries simultaneously, to compress data.
     Such as using Diavolo and XPH.

     The XPK-library do not allow packing and un-packing at the same time.
     This may change in future releases.

     We suggest before you start a backup, that you completely deactivate
     XFH, DiskExpander (etc.) and disable the compression option in Diavolo.
     The data will then be saved, as they are on the harddrive, that is,
     compressed.  You should restore the data in the same way.


   @{b}XPK Packer SHRI@{ub}

     It has often been reported that some versions of this packer do not
     function correctly.  After making a backup, it was then impossible to
     restore the data.  On these grounds, were have discontinued including
     this packer.

     To keep your data safe, you should use only the packer included.  All
     other packers or encryption methods you will be using at your own risk.


